QUESTIONS

1. In lab 4 you sent a GET request using the sockets library. What did the
sockets library do for you?
    The sockets library automatically dealt with creating and sending packets.

2. Before you submit this lab, you should check that your pcap contains the
correct traffic. What program should you use to analyze your pcap? In
your pcap, did the server send you the complete HTML for the website or
just a portion of the HTML? (Does the response end with a </html> tag?)
    I used Wireshark to analyze the pcap file. The response does not end with a </html>
    tag, but the presence of the Content-Length header suggests the whole file was transmitted.

3. Is your program guaranteed to receive a complete HTML response from
the website? Why or why not.
    No, my program is not guaranteed to receive the full HTML response because it uses sr1()
    which only captures one TCP packet. Since HTTP responses are typically split across multiple
    TCP segments, my program does not reassemble the full response and may only receive part of the HTML.

4. Can you merge the final ACK of the three-way handshake with the GET
request? That is, can you merge the two packets into one? If yes, explain
how such an option might be beneficial.
    Yes, the final ACK can be merged with the GET request by sending a single packet
    with ACK and PSH flags set and including the HTTP payload. This is beneficial because it
    reduces latency and improves efficiency by eliminating one extra packet.

5. Can scapy be used to send other types of packets? If yes, give an example.
    Yes, scapy can send ICMP, UDP, TCP and more.